    slug: "talaq-kay-masail",
    description: `Talaq Kay Masail is a comprehensive Urdu-language book that addresses the Islamic rulings and jurisprudence surrounding divorce, one of the most sensitive and frequently misunderstood areas of Muslim family law. Written in an accessible yet scholarly style, this book draws upon the primary sources of Islamic law — the Quran, authenticated Hadith, and established rulings from the four major schools of Fiqh — to present a clear and balanced understanding of how divorce is regulated in Islam. The book covers the complete spectrum of divorce-related matters including the types of divorce (Talaq-e-Sunnah and Talaq-e-Bidah), the conditions under which each type is valid, the waiting period of Iddah, the concept of Khula (wife-initiated dissolution), and the rights and responsibilities of both husband and wife during and after the divorce process.

One of the significant contributions of Talaq Kay Masail is its treatment of common misconceptions and cultural practices that have crept into Muslim communities regarding divorce. The author carefully distinguishes between what is prescribed by Islamic Sharia and what is merely cultural tradition, providing evidence-based corrections to prevalent misunderstandings. Topics such as the three-talaq-in-one-sitting issue, revocable versus irrevocable divorce, the role of arbitration and reconciliation before divorce, and the financial obligations including Mehr and maintenance are discussed in detail with references to relevant Quranic verses and prophetic traditions. The book also addresses modern scenarios and contemporary questions that Muslims face in today's context, making it a relevant resource for both scholars and laypersons.

The text is organized systematically, with chapters arranged in a logical progression that builds the reader's understanding from foundational concepts to more complex rulings. Each chapter includes supporting evidences, making it suitable for students of Islamic studies who need well-referenced material. At the same time, the language is kept straightforward enough for general readers who seek clarity on divorce matters for personal knowledge or to assist family members navigating such situations. Talaq Kay Masail serves as an important reference work that promotes informed understanding of this critical aspect of Islamic family law, helping Muslims approach divorce matters in accordance with proper Islamic guidance rather than emotion or cultural pressure.`,
